    "run_at": "2026-04-17T02:03:50.038467+00:00",
    "question": "I'm getting porosity in my flux-cored welds. What should I check?",
    "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
    "raw_final_text": "{\n  \"answer_markdown\": \"Porosity = gas pockets trapped in the bead. For flux-cored, work through this checklist in order:\\n\\n**\u26a0\ufe0f Before touching cables or the nozzle: power off and unplug the welder.**\\n\\n### 1. Check polarity first (biggest offender)\\n- **Self-shielded FCAW \u2192 DCEN** (electrode negative). If you're on DCEP, you'll get porosity almost every time.\\n- Swap the torch and work clamp leads at the front panel terminals to change polarity.\\n\\n### 2. Clean the workpiece \u2014 down to bare metal\\n- Grind or wire-brush off mill scale, rust, paint, galvanizing, and any oil or moisture.\\n- Clean the wire too \u2014 if the spool has been sitting exposed, the outermost wraps may be contaminated.\\n\\n### 3. Contact-tip-to-work distance (CTWD)\\n- Keep CTWD at \u00bd\\\" or less. A long stick-out raises the chance of atmospheric contamination at the arc.\\n\\n### 4. Maintain steady travel speed\\n- Erratic speed lets the arc sit over the puddle unevenly, trapping gas. Use two hands or brace your arm.\\n\\n### 5. Gas-shielded flux-cored only (FCAW-G)\\n- If you're running a gas-shielded flux-cored wire, also check:\\n  - Gas flow rate (increase if low, target ~15\u201320 CFH unless wire spec says otherwise)\\n  - Clean and clear the nozzle\\n  - Use the gas type the wire supplier recommends\\n\\n> Start with polarity \u2014 it's the most common cause of porosity on self-shielded flux-cored and the easiest thing to have set wrong.\",\n  \"citations\": [\n    {\n      \"doc_id\": \"owner-manual\",\n      \"source_doc\": \"owner-manual.pdf\",\n      \"page\": 37,\n      \"element_id\": \"owner-manual:page:037\",\n      \"source_kind\": \"table\",\n      \"page_image\": \"products/vulcan-omnipro-220/knowledge/pages/owner-manual/page-037.png\",\n      \"excerpt\": \"Wire Weld \u2013 Porosity: Small cavities or holes in the bead. POSSIBLE CAUSES AND SOLUTIONS 1. Incorrect polarity: Check that polarity is set correctly for type of welding. 2. Insufficient shielding gas (MIG only): Increase flow of gas. Clean nozzle. Maintain proper CTWD.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"doc_id\": \"owner-manual\",\n      \"source_doc\": \"owner-manual.pdf\",\n      \"page\": 43,\n      \"element_id\": \"owner-manual:page:043\",\n      \"source_kind\": \"table\",\n      \"page_image\": \"products/vulcan-omnipro-220/knowledge/pages/owner-manual/page-043.png\",\n      \"excerpt\": \"Troubleshooting \u2013 MIG / Flux-Cored Welding. Porosity causes: dirty workpiece or wire, incorrect polarity (MIG use DCEP; Flux-Cored self-shielded use DCEN), insufficient/incorrect shielding gas, inconsistent travel speed, CTWD too long.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"doc_id\": \"owner-manual\",\n      \"source_doc\": \"owner-manual.pdf\",\n      \"page\": 37,\n      \"element_id\": \"owner-manual:page:037\",\n      \"source_kind\": \"visual\",\n      \"page_image\": \"products/vulcan-omnipro-220/knowledge/pages/owner-manual/page-037.png\",\n      \"excerpt\": \"Diagnosis page showing porosity examples and likely causes for wire welding.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"artifacts\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"porosity-diagnosis\",\n      \"type\": \"manual_image\",\n      \"title\": \"Wire Weld Porosity Diagnosis (Manual p. 37)\",\n      \"summary\": \"Manual page showing top-view porosity examples and the full causes/solutions list for wire (MIG/flux-cored) welding.\",\n      \"source_ref\": {\n        \"doc_id\": \"owner-manual\",\n        \"source_doc\": \"owner-manual.pdf\",\n        \"page\": 37,\n        \"element_id\": \"owner-manual:page:037\"\n      },\n      \"payload\": {\n        \"path\": \"products/vulcan-omnipro-220/knowledge/pages/owner-manual/page-037.png\",\n        \"visual_id\": \"porosity-diagnosis\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"porosity-troubleshooting\",\n      \"type\": \"manual_image\",\n      \"title\": \"MIG/Flux-Cored Troubleshooting Table (Manual p. 43)\",\n      \"summary\": \"Structured troubleshooting