     "answer_markdown": "Since polarity is already ruled out, here's what the OmniPro 220 manual points to next for flux-cored pinholes/porosity:\n\n### Remaining Checks (in priority
   order)\n\n| # | Cause | What to Do |\n|---|-------|------------|\n| 1 | **Dirty base metal or wire** | Grind/wire-brush the joint down to bare metal. Make sure your wire spool is
   clean — no oil, rust, mill scale, or coatings. |\n| 2 | **CTWD too long** | Keep your contact-tip-to-work distance at **½\" or less**. A long stickout lets air contaminate the
   puddle. |\n| 3 | **Inconsistent travel speed** | Move at a steady pace. Pausing or speeding up creates irregular gas coverage and cooling. |\n| 4 | **Gas-shielded FCAW only —
   insufficient/wrong shielding gas** | If you're running gas-shielded flux-cored (not self-shielded), increase gas flow, clean the nozzle, and confirm you're using the wire
   supplier's recommended gas. *(Self-shielded FCAW needs no gas — skip this if that's your setup.)* |\n\n> ⚠️ **Power off and unplug the machine before cleaning the nozzle, swapping
   wire, or adjusting the drive roll/liner.**\n\nStart with #1 — contamination is the most common pinhole culprit after a polarity check.",
